 elementor-column elementor-field-type-submit elementor-col-100 e-form__buttons\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<button class=\"elementor-button elementor-size-sm\" type=\"submit\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"elementor-button-content-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"elementor-button-text\">Send<\/span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/span>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/button>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/form>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t<\/section>\n\t\t\t\t<section class=\"elementor-section elementor-top-section elementor-element elementor-element-efb1220 elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default\" data-id=\"efb1220\" data-element_type=\"section\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column elementor-element elementor-element-196ba2c\" data-id=\"196ba2c\" data-element_type=\"column\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-wrap elementor-element-populated\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-d34b2a4 elementor-widget elementor-widget-heading\" data-id=\"d34b2a4\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"heading.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t<h2 class=\"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default\">Habitat, Diet, and Life Cycle of Grain Beetles<\/h2>\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-be21e0e elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor\" data-id=\"be21e0e\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"text-editor.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>Grain beetles, or flour beetles, are small, reddish-brown insects that commonly infest stored grain products. They are a common pest in Canada and can be found in various locations, including homes, restaurants, grocery stores, and food processing plants. This article will explore the habitat, diet, and life cycle of grain beetles in Canada.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Habitat: <\/strong>Grain beetles are typically found in warm, dry locations, such as grain silos, flour mills, and warehouses. However, they can also infest homes and other buildings where food is stored. They are particularly attracted to grain products, such as wheat, barley, and cornmeal, but they can also be found in other food items, including pasta, spices, and pet food. Grain beetles prefer to live in areas with high humidity, so they are often found in kitchens, pantries, and basements.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Diet: <\/strong>As mentioned, grain beetles primarily feed on grain products. They are particularly attracted to products that have been stored for a long period of time or have become damp or moist. Once grain beetles infest a food item, they can quickly multiply and spread to other products. They can also be attracted to other food items like dried fruits and nuts.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Life Cycle: <\/strong>The life cycle of a grain beetle consists of four stages: egg, larva, pupa, and adult. Females can lay up to 400 eggs, which hatch in 4-12 days. The larvae then feed on the food source, molt several times, and eventually form a cocoon. After a few days in the cocoon, the larvae emerge as adults. The entire life cycle can take anywhere from 25-90 days, depending on temperature and humidity levels.<\/p>\n<p>Say goodbye to household nuisances with our comprehensive guide on eliminating grain beetles,&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/acmepestsolutions.com\/german-cockroaches-2\/\" target=\"_blank\"><u><b>drain flies<\/b><\/u><\/a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/acmepestsolutions.com\/gnats\/\" target=\"_blank\"><b><u>gnats<\/u><\/b><\/a>, and&nbsp;<a href=\"https:\/\/acmepestsolutions.com\/drain-flies\/\" target=\"_blank\"><u><b>German cockroaches<\/b><\/u><\/a>, ensuring a pest-free and comfortable living space<\/p>\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-15c192f elementor-widget elementor-widget-heading\" data-id=\"15c192f\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"heading.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t<h2 class=\"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default\">Habitat, Diet and Lifecycle of Drugstore Beetles<\/h2>\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-31e00d3 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor\" data-id=\"31e00d3\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"text-editor.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>Drugstore beetles are a type of pest that can be found in various parts of the world, including Canada. They are known for their ability to infest and damage a wide range of items, including food products, fabrics, and other organic materials. We will explore the habitat, diet, and lifecycle of drugstore beetles in Canada.<\/p><p><strong>Habitat: <\/strong>Drugstore beetles can be found in a variety of habitats in Canada, including homes, grocery stores, warehouses, and other areas where organic materials are present. They prefer warm and humid conditions and are often found in areas with high humidity levels, such as kitchens, bathrooms, and basements. They are known to infest a wide range of items, including flour, cereal, spices, pet food, and even prescription drugs.<\/p><p><strong>Diet: <\/strong>Drugstore beetles feed on a wide range of organic materials, including grains, seeds, nuts, and other dry goods. They are also known to infest animal products, such as dried meat, feathers, and wool. In homes, they can be found in kitchen pantries and cabinets, where they feed on stored food products.<\/p><p><strong>Lifecycle: <\/strong>The lifecycle of drugstore beetles begins when adult females lay their eggs on or near a food source. The larvae hatch from the eggs and begin to feed on the food source. The larvae go through several stages of development before pupating and transforming into adults. The entire lifecycle can take anywhere from two months to several years, depending on environmental conditions such as temperature and humidity.<\/p>\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-2ec27e1 elementor-widget elementor-widget-heading\" data-id=\"2ec27e1\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"heading.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t<h2 class=\"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default\">Identification Methods: Grain Beetles<\/h2>\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-40f8c4b elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor\" data-id=\"40f8c4b\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"text-editor.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>Grain beetles are small insects found in stored grains, cereals, and other dry food products. These pests can cause serious damage to food supplies and are known for their ability to reproduce quickly. To effectively control grain beetle infestations, it is important to identify them correctly.<\/p><p>One of the most common methods of identifying grain beetles is through their appearance. Grain beetles range in size from 1\/16th of an inch to 1\/8th of an inch in length and vary in color from reddish-brown to dark brown. They have oval-shaped bodies with distinctive ridges running longitudinally down the center.<\/p><p>Another method of identifying grain beetles is through their behavior. These pests are attracted to light and will often gather near windows or other light sources during the day. They are also highly mobile and can move quickly through stored foods.<\/p><p>If you suspect that you have a grain beetle infestation, it is important to take action immediately. Contacting a pest control professional can he